<div id="tabs-5" class="ui-tabs-panel" about="">
  <h2 align="center">Instructions</h2>
  
  
  <p>Where climate is "suitable" (red = 1)  malaria is likely endemic (hypo-, meso-, hyper- or holoendemic). "Suitable" areas may have little or no malaria because of malaria control. Where climate is "unsuitable" (white = 0), malaria is likely epidemic or absent. Some "unsuitable" areas may actually have endemic malaria because of the presence of surface water in an area where there is little or no precipitation. (<a class="href" href="http://www.mara.org.za/">Mapping Malaria Risk in Africa</a>)</p>
  
  
  
  
  <p> In the marginally suitable areas (0.1 - 0.9) transmission may occur. In eastern Africa transmission may occur at steady but low levels. In western and southern Africa transmission may occur in strongly seasonal cycles with great inter-annual variation. </p>
  
  
<p>
This map is a <i><u>theoretical</u></i> model based on available long-term climate data. Although it is reasonably accurate, it is <i><u>not based on actual malaria data</u></i> and may not reflect the real malaria status. </p>

